<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Quercus tomentella </i>is an evergreen tree to 20 m in height with leaves similar to those of <i>Notholithocarpus densiflorus</i>. Trees produce large acorn crops at irregular intervals. Small mammals and island scrub jays cache the acorns. Plants sprout from swollen root crowns and root suckers after damage to their trunks. Woody plants act as nurse plants moderating environmental conditions and offering seedlings and saplings protection. Plants are shade tolerant (Kindsvater 2006, Nixon and Muller 1997). <br/>
<br/>
This oak, a CNPS list 4.2 plant, is an insular endemic and relict existing in late Tertiary fossil floras on the mainland. It grows on many substrates at a wide range of elevations, most frequently on steep northwest and north-facing slopes. Kindsvater (2006) found that its site preferences are quite similar to those of many chaparral plants and that the oak exists as groves of one or several clones in several vegetation types: island oak woodland, mixed oak woodland, and closed-cone pine forest (Clark et al. 1990) on Santa Rosa Island; Junak et al. (1995, 2007) placed the groves in oak woodland, pine forest, riparian woodland, and chaparral. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Lyonothamnus floribundus </i>is endemic to the Channel Islands with two forms: <i>L. f. </i>ssp. <i>floribundus, </i>with entire, simple leaves that is endemic to Santa Catalina, and <i>L. f. </i>ssp. <i>aspleniifolius </i>with pinnately compound leaves. It occurs on all major substrate types; many are adjacent to stands of <i>Quercus pacifica </i>alliance on mesic slopes (Junak et al. 2007). Both subspecies of <i>L. floribundus</i> are CNPS list 1B.2 plants. <br/>
<br/>
On Santa Cruz and Santa Catalina islands, <i>Lyonothamnus </i>grows in discrete, small clones that are often completely dominated by the trees on upper catchments of north-facing slopes (Minnich 1980a). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
