    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bh). Stands occur on several Channel Islands including Anacapa, Santa Cruz and Santa Rosa (Rodriguez et al. 2017), as well as San Clemente and Santa Catalina (Junak et al. 2007). <i>Quercus tomentella</i> grows on five Channel Islands (Anacapa, San Clemente, Santa Catalina, Santa Cruz, and Santa Rosa) and on Guadalupe Island west of Baja California. Stands of <i>Lyonothamnus </i>have been sampled on all 4 islands on which it occurs, San Clemente, Santa Catalina, Santa Cruz, and Santa Rosa (Dixon et al. 2019, Rodriguez et al. 2017).

The simple-leaved form, <i>Lyonothamnus floribundus</i> ssp. <i>floribundus</i>, grows on Santa Catalina Island in about 200 groves with 50-100 tree stems each. The compound form, ssp. <i>aspleniifolius</i>, grows on San Clemente, Santa Cruz, and Santa Rosa islands. Some 1000 groves on Santa Cruz Island are clonal and consist of one or two genetic individuals (Bushakra et al.1999). Past maps include those for Santa Cruz Island (Junak 1987, TNC 2006) and Santa Catalina Island (Minnich 1980a, CNPS 2005). The largest clonal stand mapped on Santa Cruz Island (TNC 2006) is approximately 3 ha, but most stands are < 0.5 ha.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> For <i>Quercus tomentella</i> on Santa Rosa Island, restoration of the species has been done in areas upon removal of feral animals (Kindsvater 2006). <i>Q. tomentella</i> has had difficulty in regenerating after a 2007 fire on Santa Catalina Island with the deer present (D. Knapp, pers. comm. 2007). Populations are still in decline in areas where overgrazing by feral animals continues.

Stands with <i>Lyonothamnus </i>occur as open chaparral parks, shaped by feral animal grazing for more than a century. Earliest ground photographs of the islands from the mid- to late nineteenth century reveal dense chaparral and coastal sage scrub similar to that of the inland Santa Monica and Santa Inez mountains. <i>Lyonothamnus</i> ecology should be viewed in this historical context (Brumbaugh 1980, Minnich 1980a). With fencing and increasingly better control of feral animals, plants have been sprouting successfully on Santa Catalina Island and elsewhere (Junak et al. 2007, Knapp 2005). </div>
</div>

    

    

